      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">How the World Championship Works</h2>
      <p>The WSC uses a round-robin format over several days. Players compete in 20-30 games against different opponents. The top players then advance to knockout rounds or a final. Each game uses a chess clock with 25 minutes per player, and all games use the SOWPODS dictionary (now called Collins Scrabble Words).</p>
      <p>Entry requires qualifying through national championships or rating thresholds. Around 100-120 players from 40+ countries typically compete.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">The Growth of Competitive Scrabble</h2>
      <p>Competitive Scrabble has expanded dramatically since the 1990s. What began as a primarily North American and British pastime now spans continents, with thriving scenes in Nigeria, Kenya, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, and across Southeast Asia.</p>
      <div class="border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
        <p class="font-semibold text-purple-300 mb-2">Key Growth Milestones</p>
        <ul class="text-sm text-gray-300 space-y-1 list-disc pl-4">
          <li>1991: First WSC with 48 players from 19 countries</li>
          <li>2003: Thailand wins — first non-native English speaking champion</li>
          <li>2010s: African Scrabble surges — Nigeria fields 100+ rated players</li>
          <li>2015: Richards wins French WSC — proves Scrabble transcends language</li>
          <li>2020s: Online platforms make international play accessible year-round</li>
          <li>2024: 120+ players from 45 countries compete in Melbourne</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <p>The emergence of online Scrabble platforms has democratised competitive play. Players in regions without local clubs can now compete internationally, study top-level games, and qualify for the WSC through online rating systems.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">What Makes a World Champion?</h2>
      <p>Championship-level players share several traits that separate them from casual enthusiasts:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-sm text-gray-300 my-4 space-y-1">
        <li><strong>Vocabulary:</strong> Top players know 150,000+ valid words (the full SOWPODS dictionary)</li>
        <li><strong>Anagramming speed:</strong> Can spot 7-letter bingos within seconds</li>
        <li><strong>Board vision:</strong> See scoring opportunities 2-3 moves ahead</li>
        <li><strong>Tile tracking:</strong> Mentally track which letters remain in the bag</li>
        <li><strong>Clock discipline:</strong> Never run out of time in 25-minute games</li>
        <li><strong>Endgame mastery:</strong> Calculate exact remaining tiles and optimal final plays</li>
      </ul>

